[{"link":"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad","name":"Nadia Murad","year":2018,"category":"Peace","country":"Iraq","text":"Nadia Murad , Peace, 2018","date_of_birth":"1993-01-01T00:00:00.000","date_of_death":null,"place_of_birth":"Kocho","place_of_death":null,"gender":"female","award_age":25,"born_in":null,"mini_bio":"<p><b>Nadia Murad Basee Taha<\/b> (<a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Kurdish_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kurdish language\">Kurdish<\/a>: <span lang=\"ku\" dir=\"rtl\">\u0646\u0627\u062f\u06cc\u06d5 \u0645\u0648\u0631\u0627\u062f \u0628\u06d5\u0633\u06ce \u062a\u06d5\u06be\u0627\u060c<\/span>, <small>romanized:\u00a0<\/small><span title=\"Kurdish-language romanization\"><i lang=\"ku-Latn\">Nadiye Murad Bes\u00ea Taha<\/i><\/span>; <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Arabic_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Arabic language\">Arabic<\/a>: <span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">\u0646\u0627\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0645\u0631\u0627\u062f \u0628\u0627\u0633\u064a \u0637\u0647<\/span>; born 10 March 1993)<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad#\"cite_note-2\">[2]<\/a><\/sup> is an <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Iraq\" title=\"Iraq\">Iraqi<\/a> <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Yazidis\" title=\"Yazidis\">Yazidi<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad#\"cite_note-3\">[3]<\/a><\/sup> <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Human_rights_activists\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Human rights activists\">human rights activist<\/a> who lives in <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Germany\" title=\"Germany\">Germany<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad#\"cite_note-:0-4\">[4]<\/a><\/sup> In 2014, she was kidnapped from her hometown <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Kocho,_Iraq\" title=\"Kocho, Iraq\">Kocho<\/a> and held by the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Islamic_State_of_Iraq_and_the_Levant\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant\">Islamic State<\/a> for three months.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Newsweek-Testimony-2016_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad#\"cite_note-Newsweek-Testimony-2016-5\">[5]<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>Murad is the founder of <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Nadia%27s_Initiative\" title=\"Nadia's Initiative\">Nadia's Initiative<\/a>, an organization dedicated to \"helping women and children victimized by genocides, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Mass_Atrocity_crimes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mass Atrocity crimes\">mass atrocities<\/a>, and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Human_trafficking\" title=\"Human trafficking\">human trafficking<\/a> to heal and rebuild their lives and communities\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-FM_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad#\"cite_note-FM-6\">[6]<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>In 2018, she and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Denis_Mukwege\" title=\"Denis Mukwege\">Denis Mukwege<\/a> were jointly awarded the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Nobel_Peace_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Peace Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize<\/a> for \"their efforts to end the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Wartime_sexual_violence\" title=\"Wartime sexual violence\">use of sexual violence as a weapon of war and armed conflict<\/a>\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad#\"cite_note-7\">[7]<\/a><\/sup> She is the first Iraqi and Yazidi to be awarded a Nobel Prize.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nadia_Murad#\"cite_note-8\">[8]<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>In 2016, Murad was <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.unodc.org\/unodc\/en\/frontpage\/2016\/September\/human-trafficking-survivor-nadia-murad-named-unodc-goodwill-ambassador.html\">appointed<\/a> as the first-ever Goodwill Ambassador for the Dignity of Survivors of Human Trafficking for the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.unodc.org\/\">UNODC<\/a>).\n<\/p>","bio_image":"full\/004cb9344911fcb60abbe4efc1cf9af4d454c3e2.jpg"}]